    "125309549": {
      "title": "Electron dynamics in twisted light modes of relativistic intensity",
      "abstract": "The present work investigates the interaction of electrons with different circularly polarized twisted light pulses in the framework of relativistic particle-in-cell simulations in a fully three-dimensional geometry. It is found that the interaction is very sensitive to both the twisted light mode and the handedness of the laser. It will be shown that the twisted light pulse can be used to excite spatially structured electron beams. Depending on the chosen laser parameters, it becomes possible to drive a train of azimuthally symmetric electron bunches or to excite a discrete number of helical electron beams. The emerging electron patterns are characterized by full width at half maximum durations of the order of a few hundred attoseconds. In addition, an efficient transfer of angular momentum from the twisted light field to the particles is reported. Potentially, the proposed scheme might have interesting applications, for instance, as a diagnostic tool for ultra-fast physical systems.The present work investigates the interaction of electrons with different circularly polarized twisted light pulses in the framework of relativistic particle-in-cell simulations in a fully three-dimensional geometry. It is found that the interaction is very sensitive to both the twisted light mode and the handedness of the laser. It will be shown that the twisted light pulse can be used to excite spatially structured electron beams. Depending on the chosen laser parameters, it becomes possible to drive a train of azimuthally symmetric electron bunches or to excite a discrete number of helical electron beams. The emerging electron patterns are characterized by full width at half maximum durations of the order of a few hundred attoseconds. In addition, an efficient transfer of angular momentum from the twisted light field to the particles is reported. Potentially, the proposed scheme might have interesting applications, for instance, as a diagnostic tool for ultra-fast physical systems."
